social_posts.post_text: the @muhle_hunziken is an absolutely insane venue in all the best ways. fantastic sound and a thousand wonderfully weird little areas. it used to be a mill and feels now like an alpine mini-stadium-theater mountain  lodge designed by tim burton. there's so much to it than these photos attest to... wonderful crew and welcome and catering. we are some lucky duckies.

inspired by a friend's #teletuesday, here's my trusty travel buddy. 1970 fender telecaster, factory black, with a brass armadillo "micawber" bridge and a seymour duncan "little '59" humbucker. crooked capo by accident : ) bought in 1997 from @maindragmusic (bridge installed by @nickturno_culto, if you need guitar teching or set-ups/repairs in the denver area, he's your guy. maintained in cambridge by @imperialguitarsuk)

just finished this memoir by my friend mark hodkinson. about books, about life, the whole deal, absolutely stellar. highly recommend.

two days ago my dear aunt peg passed away, at nearly 98. i am heavy-hearted but filled with gratitude, sweet sadness mixed with celebratory feelings and boundless affection for someone who lived their life so well. she was my third parent and my north star, magical, unfailingly kind and sweet and curious and supportive. she believed in everyone's ability to be the best of themselves, but wasn't disappointed in you if you weren't. my first memories of her are watching her hands fingerpick her guitar steadily and effortlessly as she sang "blowing in the wind" and "on top of old smokey" in her lovely pure voice to me and my sister when we were tiny. ten years later, she gave me my first guitar and showed me my first chord. she encouraged me every step of the way, in everything. she had an extraordinary life, moving up to new york city from wilmington, NC, working at scribner's books (she was offered a job when she ably helped a customer who mistakenly thought she worked there), working at time magazine, teaching public school for ten years in harlem, teaching reading on channel 13 in the early 60s, getting her masters at columbia, moving to paris for two years to study, traveling solo all through europe and north africa, relocating to columbia, SC, starting two innovative and successful television shows there in which she helped students who were reading under their grade level. the shows were totally unjudgemental and had a gentle and encouraging touch which is exactly the touch she had everywhere in her life. we had so many good times and little adventures. i remember one afternoon in greenwich village where we took 20 minutes walking one block because there were some stoop sales and she needed to speak to every person, compliment what was on offer and wish them a good day. i've had so many little mini recording set-ups over the years and have enjoyed each one. this version is next to my bedroom at rockfield.

i haven't been posting much in the last ten days but we've been at rockfield, a wonderful storied studio where we made our last album, working on a new one. i bike into monmouth every morning for coffee, but aside from that we're here doing what we love the most other than playing for you.

i didn't know him personally, but i felt that tom verlaine's music somehow knew me, if that makes any sense. the way he played guitar, the words he sang, the way he sang them, resonated with me in a very natural and deep way. i am very grateful to live in the age of recorded music, and he's been a major part of why. thanks for the happy hours tom.
playing, unbelievably, tom verlaine's 1958 jazzmaster (heard on marquee moon, adventure and solo albums), owned by my dear friend @karen.glauber (who also took the photo)

ebbw vale with @nickbrine and ian laughton. behringer RD-8 sitting on a DDA console. the RD-8 is a great super-affordable roland TR-808 clone
1983 "SQ" series squier stratocaster, made in japan. $400 on reverb, plays like a dream.

if you're at sxsw this week, there's a really special panel on wednesday. my dear friend and birthday twin @karen.glauber has been putting it on for years under various names, but it's always songwriters talking about songs, and playing them. it's always people i *greatly* admire and this year is another one for the ages @colinblunstone (zombies) @brittdaniel (spoon) @macsuperchunk (superchunk) mitchellspinach (guster) and the lemon twigs, i mean... what a line-up! i wrote "so much love" for the last one and i just wrote another tune to bring. it will be a joyous time, come on over! 3/15 4pm room 18AB

yesterday's "more songs about longing" panel was a total delight. @colinblunstone (!!!) was really sweet and charming, @thelemontwigs also, was so happy to meet all three of them. @macsuperchunk played "on the floor," a beautiful song off wild loneliness (i got to sing a little harmony), colin and the twigs did a stunning version of "care of cell 44," the latter did an also stunning version of "corner of my eye," @brittdaniel, amazing as ever, sang "satellite" and "black like me." "she's not there" was last and glorious. @karen.glauber had great rapport with colin and presented the panel with heart and humor, focusing the conversation on our need for connection, always and especially post-pandemic. oh and i got to play a new song. thanks to everyone who came! and huge thanks as ever to karen for putting it all together (and for having me)✨✨✨ (📷#2 by mac)

we first met @jesse_malin in the early 90s when our old band because because because practiced in a space on west 24th street where D Generation held their Green Door parties. at the end of the decade, nada surf played at coney island high and i went to loads of shows there. in 2004 jesse asked me to sing some harmony on his second solo album. he’s always been a super-nice stand-up guy, generous with his time and energy, a vital part of new york’s music scene. he recently had a stroke and is paralyzed from the waist down. there’s a sweet relief fund to get him some help. we are making a donation and are boosting the fund’s signal in case anyone would like to do the same. we are wishing jesse a full recovery, as easy a path forward as possible and sending him all our love ❤️ link to sweet relief in bio

today i'm thinking of my father peter caws who took time away from his serious work to spend endless days with me and my sisters and show us endless kindness. we were very lucky. here he is as a young man. he held on to that easy smile forever. big love to all the dads out there ❤️

had a really nice chat with will sergeant after watching echo and the bunnymen (we played the same festival in murcia, spain). absolutely lovely guy and one of my favorite musicians in the world. teenage dream unlocked! ✨

soundtracking my walk around madrid this morning is @oyonartefino's excellent "arrecife" album. both hopeful and melancholy, it's a beautifully written and produced collection of songs. i don't understand all the words but my primitive spanish lets just enough through that i know i really like them. a forever member of spanish rock legends @losenemigosoficial, fino has been an in-demand producer for years. he and his his partner @chiuchium started a wonderful project called clovis in brooklyn years ago and i was lucky to be involved a little at the very beginning. quality people making quality music, i always look forward to hearing what they're both doing ✨✨✨. because of summer festivals and all the hot days i've spent here, i usually associate spain with warm weather, but it's great also to remember that people wear long trousers in this city, and even sweaters and jackets sometimes. lovely fall morning, i was the only one in shorts.

i was asked to provide song titles for the program, so i thought i'd share those here: inside of love / looking through / come get me / friend hospital / buried plans (minor alps) / blizzard of '77 / in front of me now (new) / always love. 

i play at 6pm, followed by the very talented duo of @sophiedequay and simon jaccard (i'll join them for a song) and then the equally talented jean-michel letalon. a bientôt!
